feeding practices. Ethiopia has undergone radical upheaval in the transition from the imperial era of Haile Selassie to the modern secular state, but the secularization of the state has been met with the widespread revival of popular religious practice. For Orthodox Christians in Zege, everything that matters about religion comes back to how one eats and fasts with others. Boylston shows how practices of feeding and avoidance have remained central even as their meaning and purpose has dramatically changed: from a means of marking class distinctions within Orthodox society, to a marker of the difference between Orthodox Christians and other religions within the contemporary Ethiopian state.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aChristianityzEthiopiavCase studies. 0aMediationxReligious aspectsxChristianityvCase studies. 0aTaboozEthiopiavCase studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aclass distinctions.  aeating.  afasting.  afeeding practices.  ahaile selassie.  ahospitality.  aimperial era.  alarge scale religious change.  alocal transformations.  amodern secular state.  anorthern ethiopia.  aorthodox christians.  aorthodox society.  aradical upheaval.  areligious traditions.  aritual prohibition.  asecularization of the state.  azege peninsula.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311066767740uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520968974zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de GruyterzOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520968974zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/do